<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="407" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1738,1982]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1738,1764]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kimmins" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[281,556,1739,1765]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abdominalis">
<emphasis box="[281,556,1739,1765]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Ascalaphus abdominalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique among its congeneric species by the well-developed abdominal tergum 4, which has a median dilation in lateral view that is covered with short black setae (
<bibRefCitation author="Kimmins, D." box="[1173,1348,1775,1801]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" pagination="1 - 29" refId="ref26581" refString="Kimmins, D. E (1949) Notes on Ascalaphidae in the British Museum collections, with descriptions of new species. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 12, 2, 1 - 29. [BotN ref  3277] https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222934908653955" type="journal article" year="1949">Kimmins 1949</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 3). Apart from the above characters, the male differs from the female in that the antennae are slightly angled at the proximal region, and the flagellomeres are basally serrated, while in the female they are straight, i.e., neither angled nor serrated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
